{"title_page": "Bret McKenzie", "text_new": "{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| honorific_suffix   = [[New Zealand Order of Merit|ONZM]]\n| name               = Bret McKenzie\n| image              = Bret McKenzie Muppets Most Wanted Premiere (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = McKenzie at the ''Muppets Most Wanted'' premiere on 11 March 2014\n| image_size         = \n| background         = solo_singer\n| birth_name         = Bret Peter Tarrant McKenzie\n| alias              = Rhymenoceros\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1976|6|29}}\n| birth_place             = [[Wellington]], [[New Zealand]]\n| instrument         = {{flatlist|\n* Guitar\n* [[Keyboard music|keyboard]]\n* bass guitar\n* drums\n* vocals\n* [[ukulele]]}}\n| genre              = {{flatlist|\n* [[Comedy music|Comedy]]\n* [[Folk music|folk]]\n* [[Acoustic music|acoustic]]}}\n| occupation         = Musician, comedian, actor\n\n| years_active       = 1994\u2013present\n| label              = [[Sub Pop]]\n| associated_acts    = {{flatlist|\n* [[Jemaine Clement]]\n* [[Flight of the Conchords]]\n* [[Wellington International Ukulele Orchestra]]\n* [[The Black Seeds]]\n* [[So You're a Man]]\n* Video Kid\n* [[The Muppets]]}}\n\n| website            = \n| current_members    = \n| past_members       = \n}}\n'''Bret Peter Tarrant McKenzie''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|ONZM}} (born 29 June 1976) is an Academy award winning New Zealand comedian, actor, musician and producer. He is one half of musical comedy duo [[Flight of the Conchords]] along with [[Jemaine Clement]]. The duo's comedy and music became the basis of a [[Flight of the Conchords (radio series)|BBC radio series]] and then an oft-lauded [[Flight of the Conchords (TV series)|American television series]], which aired for two seasons on [[HBO]]. McKenzie served as music supervisor for two [[The Muppets|Muppet]] films, ''[[The Muppets (film)|The Muppets]] ''(2011) and ''[[Muppets Most Wanted]] ''(2014), the former of which won him an [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] for the song \"[[Man or Muppet]]\". His latest work has seen him write the lyrics to the 2016 [[Sainsburys]] Christmas advert featuring [[James Corden]] on vocals.<ref>\nhttps://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/sainsbury-s-christmas-advert-2016-5-things-you-need-to-know-about-the-greatest-gift-a3393691.html</ref>\n\nAs an actor, he portrayed [[Lindir]] in [[Peter Jackson]]'s [[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|''The Lord of the Rings'']] and [[The Hobbit (film series)|''The Hobbit'']] film trilogies: in the first he remained unnamed with fans naming him [[Figwit]], a character originally cast as an extra who gained attention thanks to the trilogy's [[Fandom|fan community]], and in ''The Hobbit'' is credited as [[Lindir]], a small character who originally appears in the book of ''[[The Fellowship of the Ring]]''.\n\n==Background==\nMcKenzie was born in [[Wellington]], [[New Zealand]]. He is a former member of [[The Black Seeds]]. He released an album called ''Prototype'' as Video Kid<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videokid.tv/ |title=Video Kid |access-date=24 November 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051016031650/http://www.videokid.tv/ |archive-date=16 October 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and is a member of the [[Wellington International Ukulele Orchestra]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukulele.co.nz |title=Wellington International Ukulele Orchestra}}</ref> McKenzie attended Clifton Terrace Model School (\"model\" refers to a standard school for training teachers as opposed to [[model (person)|modelling]]), [[Wellington College (New Zealand)|Wellington College]] and then [[Victoria University of Wellington]] where he met [[Jemaine Clement]] who was also studying film and theatre. Together, they were members of [[So You're a Man]] and they later formed Flight of the Conchords.\n\nAs Flight of the Conchords they have toured internationally and released four CDs: ''[[Folk the World Tour]]'' in 2002,''[[The Distant Future]]'' (which won the [[Grammy Award for Best Comedy Album]]) in 2007, the Grammy nominated ''[[Flight of the Conchords (album)|Flight of the Conchords]]'' in 2008, and ''[[I Told You I Was Freaky]]'' in 2009. The Conchords produced a six-part improvisational comedy radio program for the [[BBC]] and have appeared on ''[[Late Night with Conan O'Brien]]'', the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'' and ''[[The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson]]''. After a successful appearance in 2005 on [[Home Box Office|HBO]]s ''[[One Night Stand (US TV series)|One Night Stand]]'', the Conchords were offered their own 12-part HBO series ''[[Flight of the Conchords (TV series)|Flight of the Conchords]]''.  Its first season ran from June to September 2007, and its second season premiered on HBO 18 January 2009.\n\nMcKenzie has appeared in the first and third films in [[Peter Jackson]]'s ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'' trilogy. His silent role in the first film as [[Figwit]] achieved some minor internet fame, which led to Jackson giving him a line in the third film. In April 2011, McKenzie was cast as the elf [[Lindir]] for ''[[The Hobbit (film series)|The Hobbit]]''. His father [[Peter McKenzie (actor)|Peter McKenzie]] played the role of [[Elendil]] in ''Lord of the Rings''.\n\nAlong with Clement, McKenzie was featured as one of 2008's \"100 Sexiest People\" in a special edition of the Australian magazine [[Who (magazine)|''Who'']].\n\nMcKenzie and fellow Conchord Clement guest starred as a pair of camp counselors in \"[[Elementary School Musical (The Simpsons)|Elementary School Musical]]\", the season premiere of the [[The Simpsons (season 22)|22nd]] season of ''[[The Simpsons]]'', which aired on 26 September 2010.<ref name=\"Simpsons\">{{Cite web|title=Gleeful over Glee: Cory Monteith to appear on The Simpsons|author=Strachan, Alex|url=http://www.canada.com/Gleeful+over+Glee+Cory+Monteith+appear+Simpsons/3350970/story.html|publisher=[[Canada.com]]|date=2 August 2010|accessdate=2010-08-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111028000202/http://www2.canada.com/gleeful+over+glee+cory+monteith+appear+simpsons/3350970/story.html|archivedate=28 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring the summer of 2010, McKenzie flew to Los Angeles to serve as the music supervisor for [[The Muppets (film)|''The Muppets'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/film/4442796/Conchords-star-flies-south-for-new-film|title=Conchords star flies south|work=Stuff|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> He went on to write four of the five original songs from the film's soundtrack including \"Man or Muppet\" and \"Life's a Happy Song\" both of which were nominated for [[Broadcast Film Critics Association Awards]] and [[Satellite Awards]] for Best Original Song.<ref>[[Satellite Award for Best Original Song]]</ref>\n\nAt the [[84th Academy Awards]] in 2012 his song, \"[[Man or Muppet]]\", won the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]].\n\nMcKenzie, together with Australian comedian [[Hamish Blake]] starred in a New Zealand feature film, ''[[Two Little Boys (film)|Two Little Boys]]'', finished in late 2011 and released in New Zealand on March 2012.<ref name=\"DailyTelegraphAust_09Dec2010_SydneyConfidential_HamishBlaketostarwithBretMcKenzieinSarkies'TwoLittleBoys\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/hamish-blake-to-star-with-bret-mckenzie-in-sarkies-two-little-boys/story-e6frewz0-1225968460210|title=Hamish Blake to star with Bret McKenzie in Sarkies' Two Little Boys  |last=Catanzariti|first=Katelyn|date=9 December 2010|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|accessdate=9 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2012 Birthday Honours (New Zealand)|2012 Queen's Birthday and Diamond Jubilee Honours]], McKenzie was appointed an [[Officer of the New Zealand Order of Merit]], for services to music and film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dpmc.govt.nz/publications/queens-birthday-and-diamond-jubilee-honours-list-2012 |title=Queen's Birthday and Diamond Jubilee honours list 2012 |date=4 June 2012 |publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet |accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nMcKenzie wrote the original songs for the 2014 movie ''[[Muppets Most Wanted]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is married to New Zealand publicist Hannah Clarke<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/lifestyle/news/article.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=10562875 | title=Bride of the Conchord - Bret marries childhood sweetheart| work=New Zealand Herald | date=22 March 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-21 | first=Rebecca | last=Lewis}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/2278386/Conchord-has-wings-clipped|title=Conchord has wings clipped|publisher=[[Fairfax New Zealand]]|date=20 March 2009|accessdate=2009-05-17}}</ref> and currently maintains residences in [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City]], and [[Wellington]]. They have three children and mainly live in Wellington.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/music/news/article.cfm?c_id=264&objectid=10607282 |title=Fatherhood keeps 'Conchords' stars busy |work=New Zealand Herald |date=5 November 2009 |accessdate=2009-11-08 |first=Jacqueline |last=Smith}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|2012\n|[[Academy Awards]]\n|Best Original Song - \"Man or Muppet\"\n|''The Muppets'' \n|-\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Character\n! Format\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring]]''\n| [[Figwit|Lindir]]<ref name=\"Variety Hobbit\" /><!--DO NOT ADD \"FIGWIT\". IT IS A CULT NAME, IT IS NOT WHAT HE IS CREDITED AS-->\n| Feature film\n| Uncredited cameo\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]''\n| Lindir<ref name=\"Variety Hobbit\" /> <!--DO NOT ADD \"FIGWIT\". IT IS A CULT NAME, IT IS NOT WHAT HE IS CREDITED AS-->\n| Feature film\n| \n|-\n| 2007\u20132009\n| ''[[Flight of the Conchords (TV series)|Flight of the Conchords]]''\n| Bret McClegnie<!-- the character name is not the same as McKenzie's real name, although it's similar--><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/feb/10/familyandrelationships.television |title=The accidental sex gods |last=Vernon |first=Polly |date=9 February 2008 |work=[[The Observer]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |accessdate=30 June 2013}}</ref>\n| TV series\n| Also creator, co-writer, and executive producer\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[The Drinky Crow Show]]''\n| Rob, the Alien\n| TV series\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Tim and Eric Awesome Show, Great Job!]]''\n| Tim's Tennis Double\n| TV series\n| Episode: \"[[List of Tim and Eric Awesome Show, Great Job! episodes#Season 4: 2009|Tennis]]\"\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Diagnosis Death]]''\n| Dr. Cruise\n| Film\n| \n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[The Simpsons]]''\n| Kurt Hardwick\n| TV series\n| Episode: \"[[Elementary School Musical (The Simpsons)|Elementary School Musical]]\"<ref name=\"Simpsons\" />\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[The Muppets (film)|The Muppets]]''\n| \n| Feature Film\n| Music supervisor and writer of original songs<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/20/magazine/bret-mckenzie-muppets.html |title=On Composing for Kermit the Frog |last=Sternbergh |first=Adam |date=17 November 2011 |work=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref> <br>[[Academy Award for Best Original Song]]\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Two Little Boys (film)|Two Little Boys]]''\n| Nige\n| Feature Film\n| \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey]]''\n| Lindir<ref name=\"Variety Hobbit\">{{cite web |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118034972 |title='Conchords' star McKenzie an elf in 'The Hobbit' |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=4 April 2011 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[PMC (company)|Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=4 April 2011}}</ref>\n| Feature Film\n| Cameo\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Austenland (film)|Austenland]]''\n| Martin\n| Feature Film\n| \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Muppets Most Wanted]]''\n| \n| Feature Film\n| Music supervisor and original songwriter<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collider.com/the-muppets-2-sequel-news/208626/ |title=THE MUPPETS Sequel Update: Filming Begins in Late January at Pinewood Studios in London; Bret McKenzie Writing New Songs |last=Weintraub |first=Steve |date=5 November 2012 |work=Collider |publisher=Demand Media Entertainment |accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-disney-cancels-little-mermaid-3d-pirates-5-2015-20130114,0,6139988.story |title=Disney cancels 'Little Mermaid 3-D,' dates 'Pirates 5' for 2015 |last=Fritz |first=Ben |date=15 January 2013 |newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=14 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/tina-fey-disneys-muppets-sequel-409623 |title=Tina Fey in Talks to Join Disney's 'Muppets' Sequel (Exclusive) |last=Kit |first=Borys |date=8 January 2013 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |accessdate=9 January 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Bajillion Dollar Propertie$]]''\n| Huck\n| TV series\n| Episode: \"Looking Forward\"\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Flight of the Conchords: Live in London'' \n| Himself \n| TV special\n| Also writer and producer\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|TBA\n| ''Bob the Musical''\n| \n| rowspan=\"3\"|Feature Film\n| Songwriter<ref>{{cite news|last=Kit|first=Borys|title=Michael Chabon to Write Disney's 'Bob the Musical' (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/michael-chabon-write-disneys-bob-811245|date=27 July 2015|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Moonland''<ref>{{cite news|last=Crittenton|first=Anya|title=BRET MCKENZIE OF FLIGHT OF THE CONCHORDS WRITING FANTASY FILM FOR WARNER BROS. (EXCLUSIVE)|url=http://www.tracking-board.com/bret-mckenzie-of-flight-of-the-conchords-writing-fantasy-film-for-warner-bros-exclusive/|date=8 August 2016|website=The Tracking Board|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n| \n| rowspan=\"2\"| Writer, songwriter\n|-\n| ''[[Emmet Otter's Jug-Band Christmas#Film adaptation|Emmet Otter's Jug-Band Christmas]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=Bret McKenzie to Develop New Film Adaptation of 'Emmet Otter's Jug-Band Christmas'|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2019/10/21/bret-mckenzie-to-develop-new-film-adaptation-of-emmet-otters-jug-band-christmas/|date=21 October 2019|website=Film Music Reporter}}</ref>\n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{IMDb name|1235366|Bret McKenzie}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111118040135/http://flightoftheconchords.co.nz/ Flight of the Conchords Official Site]\n* [http://www.whatthefolk.net/ What The Folk! Flight of the Conchords fan site]\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio2/comedy/conchords.shtml BBC Radio 2]\n* [https://www.myspace.com/conchords Flight of the Conchords Official MySpace]\n\n{{Flight of the Conchords}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Bret McKenzie\n| list = \n{{AcademyAwardBestOriginalSong 2011\u20132020}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Song}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McKenzie, Bret}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Best Original Song Academy Award-winning songwriters]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Flight of the Conchords members]]\n[[Category:People educated at Wellington College (New Zealand)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male comedians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Wellington]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male television actors]]\n[[Category:People from Wellington City]]\n[[Category:The Black Seeds members]]\n[[Category:Officers of the New Zealand Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand male actors]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male singers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male film actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| honorific_suffix   = [[New Zealand Order of Merit|ONZM]]\n| name               = Bret McKenzie\n| image              = Bret McKenzie Muppets Most Wanted Premiere (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = McKenzie at the ''Muppets Most Wanted'' premiere on 11 March 2014\n| image_size         = \n| background         = solo_singer\n| birth_name         = Bret Peter Tarrant McKenzie\n| alias              = Rhymenoceros\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1976|6|29}}\n| birth_place             = [[Wellington]], [[New Zealand]]\n| instrument         = {{flatlist|\n* Guitar\n* [[Keyboard music|keyboard]]\n* bass guitar\n* drums\n* vocals\n* [[ukulele]]}}\n| genre              = {{flatlist|\n* [[Comedy music|Comedy]]\n* [[Folk music|folk]]\n* [[Acoustic music|acoustic]]}}\n| occupation         = Musician, comedian, actor\n\n| years_active       = 1994\u2013present\n| label              = [[Sub Pop]]\n| associated_acts    = {{flatlist|\n* [[Jemaine Clement]]\n* [[Flight of the Conchords]]\n* [[Wellington International Ukulele Orchestra]]\n* [[The Black Seeds]]\n* [[So You're a Man]]\n* Video Kid\n* [[The Muppets]]}}\n\n| website            = \n| current_members    = \n| past_members       = \n}}\n'''Bret Peter Tarrant McKenzie''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|ONZM}} (born 29 June 1976) is an Academy Award-Winning, New Zealand comedian, actor, musician and producer. He is one half of musical comedy duo [[Flight of the Conchords]] along with [[Jemaine Clement]]. The duo's comedy and music became the basis of a [[Flight of the Conchords (radio series)|BBC radio series]] and then an oft-lauded [[Flight of the Conchords (TV series)|American television series]], which aired for two seasons on [[HBO]]. McKenzie served as music supervisor for two [[The Muppets|Muppet]] films, ''[[The Muppets (film)|The Muppets]] ''(2011) and ''[[Muppets Most Wanted]] ''(2014), the former of which won him an [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] for the song \"[[Man or Muppet]]\". His latest work has seen him write the lyrics to the 2016 [[Sainsburys]] Christmas advert featuring [[James Corden]] on vocals.<ref>\nhttps://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/sainsbury-s-christmas-advert-2016-5-things-you-need-to-know-about-the-greatest-gift-a3393691.html</ref>\n\nAs an actor, he portrayed [[Lindir]] in [[Peter Jackson]]'s [[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|''The Lord of the Rings'']] and [[The Hobbit (film series)|''The Hobbit'']] film trilogies: in the first he remained unnamed with fans naming him [[Figwit]], a character originally cast as an extra who gained attention thanks to the trilogy's [[Fandom|fan community]], and in ''The Hobbit'' is credited as [[Lindir]], a small character who originally appears in the book of ''[[The Fellowship of the Ring]]''.\n\n==Background==\nMcKenzie was born in [[Wellington]], [[New Zealand]]. He is a former member of [[The Black Seeds]]. He released an album called ''Prototype'' as Video Kid<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videokid.tv/ |title=Video Kid |access-date=24 November 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051016031650/http://www.videokid.tv/ |archive-date=16 October 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and is a member of the [[Wellington International Ukulele Orchestra]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukulele.co.nz |title=Wellington International Ukulele Orchestra}}</ref> McKenzie attended Clifton Terrace Model School (\"model\" refers to a standard school for training teachers as opposed to [[model (person)|modelling]]), [[Wellington College (New Zealand)|Wellington College]] and then [[Victoria University of Wellington]] where he met [[Jemaine Clement]] who was also studying film and theatre. Together, they were members of [[So You're a Man]] and they later formed Flight of the Conchords.\n\nAs Flight of the Conchords they have toured internationally and released four CDs: ''[[Folk the World Tour]]'' in 2002,''[[The Distant Future]]'' (which won the [[Grammy Award for Best Comedy Album]]) in 2007, the Grammy nominated ''[[Flight of the Conchords (album)|Flight of the Conchords]]'' in 2008, and ''[[I Told You I Was Freaky]]'' in 2009. The Conchords produced a six-part improvisational comedy radio program for the [[BBC]] and have appeared on ''[[Late Night with Conan O'Brien]]'', the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'' and ''[[The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson]]''. After a successful appearance in 2005 on [[Home Box Office|HBO]]s ''[[One Night Stand (US TV series)|One Night Stand]]'', the Conchords were offered their own 12-part HBO series ''[[Flight of the Conchords (TV series)|Flight of the Conchords]]''.  Its first season ran from June to September 2007, and its second season premiered on HBO 18 January 2009.\n\nMcKenzie has appeared in the first and third films in [[Peter Jackson]]'s ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'' trilogy. His silent role in the first film as [[Figwit]] achieved some minor internet fame, which led to Jackson giving him a line in the third film. In April 2011, McKenzie was cast as the elf [[Lindir]] for ''[[The Hobbit (film series)|The Hobbit]]''. His father [[Peter McKenzie (actor)|Peter McKenzie]] played the role of [[Elendil]] in ''Lord of the Rings''.\n\nAlong with Clement, McKenzie was featured as one of 2008's \"100 Sexiest People\" in a special edition of the Australian magazine [[Who (magazine)|''Who'']].\n\nMcKenzie and fellow Conchord Clement guest starred as a pair of camp counselors in \"[[Elementary School Musical (The Simpsons)|Elementary School Musical]]\", the season premiere of the [[The Simpsons (season 22)|22nd]] season of ''[[The Simpsons]]'', which aired on 26 September 2010.<ref name=\"Simpsons\">{{Cite web|title=Gleeful over Glee: Cory Monteith to appear on The Simpsons|author=Strachan, Alex|url=http://www.canada.com/Gleeful+over+Glee+Cory+Monteith+appear+Simpsons/3350970/story.html|publisher=[[Canada.com]]|date=2 August 2010|accessdate=2010-08-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111028000202/http://www2.canada.com/gleeful+over+glee+cory+monteith+appear+simpsons/3350970/story.html|archivedate=28 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring the summer of 2010, McKenzie flew to Los Angeles to serve as the music supervisor for [[The Muppets (film)|''The Muppets'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/film/4442796/Conchords-star-flies-south-for-new-film|title=Conchords star flies south|work=Stuff|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> He went on to write four of the five original songs from the film's soundtrack including \"Man or Muppet\" and \"Life's a Happy Song\" both of which were nominated for [[Broadcast Film Critics Association Awards]] and [[Satellite Awards]] for Best Original Song.<ref>[[Satellite Award for Best Original Song]]</ref>\n\nAt the [[84th Academy Awards]] in 2012 his song, \"[[Man or Muppet]]\", won the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]].\n\nMcKenzie, together with Australian comedian [[Hamish Blake]] starred in a New Zealand feature film, ''[[Two Little Boys (film)|Two Little Boys]]'', finished in late 2011 and released in New Zealand on March 2012.<ref name=\"DailyTelegraphAust_09Dec2010_SydneyConfidential_HamishBlaketostarwithBretMcKenzieinSarkies'TwoLittleBoys\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/hamish-blake-to-star-with-bret-mckenzie-in-sarkies-two-little-boys/story-e6frewz0-1225968460210|title=Hamish Blake to star with Bret McKenzie in Sarkies' Two Little Boys  |last=Catanzariti|first=Katelyn|date=9 December 2010|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|accessdate=9 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2012 Birthday Honours (New Zealand)|2012 Queen's Birthday and Diamond Jubilee Honours]], McKenzie was appointed an [[Officer of the New Zealand Order of Merit]], for services to music and film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dpmc.govt.nz/publications/queens-birthday-and-diamond-jubilee-honours-list-2012 |title=Queen's Birthday and Diamond Jubilee honours list 2012 |date=4 June 2012 |publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet |accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nMcKenzie wrote the original songs for the 2014 movie ''[[Muppets Most Wanted]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is married to New Zealand publicist Hannah Clarke<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/lifestyle/news/article.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=10562875 | title=Bride of the Conchord - Bret marries childhood sweetheart| work=New Zealand Herald | date=22 March 2009 | accessdate=2009-05-21 | first=Rebecca | last=Lewis}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/2278386/Conchord-has-wings-clipped|title=Conchord has wings clipped|publisher=[[Fairfax New Zealand]]|date=20 March 2009|accessdate=2009-05-17}}</ref> and currently maintains residences in [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City]], and [[Wellington]]. They have three children and mainly live in Wellington.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/music/news/article.cfm?c_id=264&objectid=10607282 |title=Fatherhood keeps 'Conchords' stars busy |work=New Zealand Herald |date=5 November 2009 |accessdate=2009-11-08 |first=Jacqueline |last=Smith}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|2012\n|[[Academy Awards]]\n|Best Original Song - \"Man or Muppet\"\n|''The Muppets'' \n|-\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Character\n! Format\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring]]''\n| [[Figwit|Lindir]]<ref name=\"Variety Hobbit\" /><!--DO NOT ADD \"FIGWIT\". IT IS A CULT NAME, IT IS NOT WHAT HE IS CREDITED AS-->\n| Feature film\n| 