 |title='Conchords' star McKenzie an elf in 'The Hobbit' |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=4 April 2011 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[PMC (company)|Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=4 April 2011}}</ref>\n| Feature Film\n| Cameo\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Austenland (film)|Austenland]]''\n| Martin\n| Feature Film\n| \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Muppets Most Wanted]]''\n| \n| Feature Film\n| Music supervisor and original songwriter<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collider.com/the-muppets-2-sequel-news/208626/ |title=THE MUPPETS Sequel Update: Filming Begins in Late January at Pinewood Studios in London; Bret McKenzie Writing New Songs |last=Weintraub |first=Steve |date=5 November 2012 |work=Collider |publisher=Demand Media Entertainment |accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-disney-cancels-little-mermaid-3d-pirates-5-2015-20130114,0,6139988.story |title=Disney cancels 'Little Mermaid 3-D,' dates 'Pirates 5' for 2015 |last=Fritz |first=Ben |date=15 January 2013 |newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=14 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/tina-fey-disneys-muppets-sequel-409623 |title=Tina Fey in Talks to Join Disney's 'Muppets' Sequel (Exclusive) |last=Kit |first=Borys |date=8 January 2013 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |accessdate=9 January 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Bajillion Dollar Propertie$]]''\n| Huck\n| TV series\n| Episode: \"Looking Forward\"\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Flight of the Conchords: Live in London'' \n| Himself \n| TV special\n| Also writer and producer\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|TBA\n| ''Bob the Musical''\n| \n| rowspan=\"3\"|Feature Film\n| Songwriter<ref>{{cite news|last=Kit|first=Borys|title=Michael Chabon to Write Disney's 'Bob the Musical' (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/michael-chabon-write-disneys-bob-811245|date=27 July 2015|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Moonland''<ref>{{cite news|last=Crittenton|first=Anya|title=BRET MCKENZIE OF FLIGHT OF THE CONCHORDS WRITING FANTASY FILM FOR WARNER BROS. (EXCLUSIVE)|url=http://www.tracking-board.com/bret-mckenzie-of-flight-of-the-conchords-writing-fantasy-film-for-warner-bros-exclusive/|date=8 August 2016|website=The Tracking Board|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n| \n| rowspan=\"2\"| Writer, songwriter\n|-\n| ''[[Emmet Otter's Jug-Band Christmas#Film adaptation|Emmet Otter's Jug-Band Christmas]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=Bret McKenzie to Develop New Film Adaptation of 'Emmet Otter's Jug-Band Christmas'|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2019/10/21/bret-mckenzie-to-develop-new-film-adaptation-of-emmet-otters-jug-band-christmas/|date=21 October 2019|website=Film Music Reporter}}</ref>\n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{IMDb name|1235366|Bret McKenzie}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111118040135/http://flightoftheconchords.co.nz/ Flight of the Conchords Official Site]\n* [http://www.whatthefolk.net/ What The Folk! Flight of the Conchords fan site]\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio2/comedy/conchords.shtml BBC Radio 2]\n* [https://www.myspace.com/conchords Flight of the Conchords Official MySpace]\n\n{{Flight of the Conchords}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Bret McKenzie\n| list = \n{{AcademyAwardBestOriginalSong 2011\u20132020}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Song}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McKenzie, Bret}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Best Original Song Academy Award-winning songwriters]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Flight of the Conchords members]]\n[[Category:People educated at Wellington College (New Zealand)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male comedians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Wellington]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male television actors]]\n[[Category:People from Wellington City]]\n[[Category:The Black Seeds members]]\n[[Category:Officers of the New Zealand Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand male actors]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male singers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male film actors]]\n", "name_user": "Spartan", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor edit to the punctuation of this paragraph", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bret_McKenzie"}
{"title_page": "Griffith J. Griffith", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman, philanthropist}}\n{{for|other people with the same name|Griffith Griffith (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Griffith J. Griffith\n| image       = Griffith Jenkins Griffith.jpg\n| image_size                =\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name                = Griffith Jenkins Griffith\n| birth_date                = {{birth date|1850|1|4}}\n| birth_place               = [[Bettws, Bridgend|Bettws]], [[Glamorgan]]shire, Wales\n| death_date                = {{death date and age|1919|7|6|1850|1|4}}\n| death_place               = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| body_discovered           =\n| resting_place             = [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery|Hollywood Memorial Cemetery]]<br>Los Angeles\n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| residence                 =\n| nationality               =\n| ethnicity                 =\n| citizenship               =\n| other_names               = Colonel Griffith J. Griffith\n| known_for                 = [[Philanthropy]]\n| education                 =\n| alma_mater                =\n| employer                  =\n| notable works             =\n| occupation                = [[Journalist]]<br>[[Mining]] and real estate magnate\n| years_active              =\n| home_town                 =\n| salary                    =\n| networth                  =\n| height                    =\n| weight                    =\n| title                     =\n| term                      =\n| predecessor               =\n| successor                 =\n| party                     =\n| opponents                 =\n| boards                    =\n| religion                  =\n| spouse                    = Mary Agnes Christina Mesmer (1887\u20131904; divorced)\n| partner                   =\n| children                  = Van M. Griffith (1888\u20131974)\n| parents                   =\n| relations                 =\n| callsign                  =\n| awards                    =\n| signature                 =\n| signature_alt             =\n| website                   =\n| footnotes                 =\n| box_width                 =\n| misc                      =\n}}\n\n'''Griffith Jenkins Griffith''' (January 4, 1850 \u2013 July 6, 1919) was a Welsh-born American [[industrialist]] and [[philanthropist]]. After amassing a significant fortune from a [[mining|mining syndicate]] in the 1880s, Griffith donated {{convert|3015|acre|km2}} to the [[Los Angeles|City of Los Angeles]] which became [[Griffith Park]], and he bequeathed the money to build the park's [[Greek Theatre (Los Angeles)|Greek Theatre]] and [[Griffith Observatory]]. Griffith's legacy was marred by his notorious shooting of his wife in 1903, a crime for which he served two years in prison.\n\n==Life==\n\n===Career and philanthropy===\n[[File:GriffithJGriffithStatue01.JPG|240px|thumb|Bronze statue of Griffith J. Griffith at [[Griffith Park]], Los Angeles (installed 1996)]]\nGriffith J. Griffith was born in [[Bettws, Bridgend|Bettws]], [[Glamorgan]]shire, [[Wales]], on January 4, 1850.<ref name=\"BBC historical\">{{cite web|title=BBC \u2013 south east Wales historical figures \u2013 Griffith J Griffith |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/southeast/halloffame/historical_figures/colonel_griffith.shtml|accessdate=May 14, 2010 |publisher=[[BBC]]|date=May 14, 2010|work=BBC website }}</ref> He immigrated to the United States in 1865, settling in [[Ashland, Pennsylvania]]. In 1873 he moved to San Francisco, California, and became manager of the Herald Publishing Company. In 1887 he married Mary Agnes Christina Mesmer (1864\u20131948).<ref>[http://www.ulwaf.com/LA-1900s/04.11.html#GriffithDivorce ''Los Angeles Daily Examiner''], November 5, 1904</ref>\n\nIn 1878 G. J. Griffith became mining correspondent for the ''Alta California'', a San Francisco newspaper. As a reporter he gained extensive knowledge of the mining industry on the Pacific Coast and in Nevada, which led to his employment by various mining syndicates. As a mining expert, Griffith acquired a fortune.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/expat/expatlife/8751943/The-Britons-who-made-their-mark-on-LA.html|title=The Britons who made their mark on LA|date=2011-09-11|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nIn 1882 Griffith moved to Los Angeles and purchased approximately {{convert|4000|acre|km2}} of the [[Rancho Los Feliz]] Mexican land grant. On December 16, 1896, Griffith and his wife Christina presented {{convert|3015|acre|km2}} of the Rancho Los Feliz to the city of Los Angeles for use as a public park. Griffith called it \"a Christmas present.\" After accepting the donation, the city passed an ordinance to name the property Griffith Park, in honor of the donor.<ref>\"Death Claims G. J. Griffith,\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', July 7, 1919</ref>\n\n\"It must be made a place of rest and relaxation for the masses, a resort for the rank and file, for the plain people,\" Griffith told the Los Angeles City Council when he donated the land. \"I consider it my obligation to make Los Angeles a happy, cleaner, and finer city. I wish to pay my debt of duty in this way to the community in which I have prospered.\" <ref>[http://www.ci.la.ca.us/RAP/dos/parks/griffithPK/gp_narrative.htm Griffith Park narrative] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115220537/http://www.ci.la.ca.us/rap/dos/parks/griffithpk/gp_narrative.htm |date=2010-01-15 }}, Department of Recreation and Parks, City of Los Angeles</ref>\n\nGriffith later donated another {{convert|1000|acre|km2}} along the [[Los Angeles River]].<ref>\"Griffith Park To Be Considered For Monument Status\"; Walton, Alice, City News Service, August 21, 2008</ref>\n\n===Crime===\nWhile vacationing in [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]] on September 3, 1903, Griffith shot his wife in the presidential suite of the [[:c:Category:Hotel Arcadia (Santa Monica, California)|Arcadia Hotel]], as she knelt on the floor before him. The shot did not kill her, but she was left disfigured and lost her right eye. Griffith was charged with assault with a deadly weapon with intent to commit murder. The prosecution was led by [[Henry Gage|Henry T. Gage]], former [[governor of California]]. Griffith was defended by attorney [[Earl Rogers]], whose cross-examination of the veiled Mrs. Griffith revealed that her husband\u2014generally thought to be a [[teetotaler]]\u2014was in fact a secret [[alcoholism|drunk]] who was subject to [[paranoia|paranoid]] delusions. Griffith was convicted of a lesser charge, assault with a deadly weapon. The judge sentenced him to two years in [[San Quentin State Prison]], instructing that he be given \"medical aid for his condition of alcoholic insanity\".<ref>[[Adela Rogers St. Johns|St. Johns, Adela Rogers]], ''Final Verdict''. Garden City, New York: Doubleday & Company, Inc., 1962, pp. 220\u2013239. \"That was where Earl Rogers began the first alcoholic [[insanity defense]],\" St. Johns wrote. \"Perhaps the first\u2014certainly one of the first\u2014times that alcohol was called to account in an American courtroom as a disease, a [[mental illness]], not just a sin or a crime or an indulgence\". (''Final Verdict'', p. 232.)</ref>\n\nOn November 4, 1904, while he was in prison, Mrs. Griffith was granted a divorce on the grounds of cruelty, and she was awarded custody of their 16-year-old son Vandell. The court also stated that G. J. Griffith would pay for his son's education at [[Stanford University]]. The decree was made in the record time of four and a half minutes.<ref>\"Mrs. Griffith Gets Divorce,\" ''Los Angeles Times'', November 5, 1904</ref>\n\n===Later life===\nG. J. Griffith was released from prison December 3, 1906, after serving nearly two years. His conduct at the penitentiary was called exemplary. Griffith returned to Los Angeles and began lecturing on prison reform.<ref>\"Griffith is Freed Today,\" ''Los Angeles Times'', December 3, 1906; \"Griffith to Lecture: Gone to San Francisco to Advocate Prison Reform Along Elmira Institution Lines,\" ''Los Angeles Times'', January 26, 1908</ref>\n\nIn December 1912 Griffith offered a second \"Christmas present\" to Los Angeles, in the form of a Greek Theater and a Hall of Science to be built at his expense in Griffith Park. The offer was accepted by the City Council, but members of the Park Commission objected and instituted a court action to block the donation. Griffith left the offer in his will. He died of liver disease on July 6, 1919. The bulk of his $1.5 million estate was bequeathed to the city for the building of the [[Greek Theater (Los Angeles)|Greek Theater]] (1929) and [[Griffith Observatory]] (1935).<ref>\"Death Claims G. J. Griffith,\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', July 7, 1919; \"City Gains by Griffith Will,\" ''Los Angeles Times'', July 12, 1919</ref> He is interred at the [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery]] in Los Angeles in the north end of Section 7, a.k.a. \"The Griffith Lawn\".<ref name=\"russell\">Russell, Ron (July 3, 1988). If you stand at the side of his obelisk and look north, you will see the Griffith Observatory. Splendor Fades at Final Resting Place of Famous, Almost Famous. ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''</ref>\n\nGriffith used the title of [[Colonel]], but official records of military service which support this rank have not been found. Evidence suggests the only military title he ever held was Major of rifle practice with the [[California National Guard]].<ref name=\"gurstelle2006\">Gurstelle, William (2006). ''Adventures from the Technology Underground.''  Clarkson Potter {{ISBN|978-1-4000-5082-6}}</ref><ref name=\"bell2011\">Bell, Alison (June 12, 2011). [http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0612-then-20110612,0,5448370.story Colonel Griffith J. Griffith one of L.A.'s more colorful figures.] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Toomanylinks|date=January 2020}}\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/southeast/halloffame/historical_figures/colonel_griffith.shtml BBC biography]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100115220537/http://www.ci.la.ca.us/rap/dos/parks/griffithpk/gp_narrative.htm Griffith Park Narrative] (City of Los Angeles)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080513065309/http://www.griffithobservatory.org/obshist.html Griffith Observatory History]\n*[http://english.glendale.cc.ca.us/colonel.html Glendale College biography]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/1903/09/07/archives/millionaire-under-arrest-the-wife-of-col-griffith-of-los-angeles.html Millionaire Under Arrest; The Wife of Col. Griffith of Los Angeles Says He Shot Her]; ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 7, 1903\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061115071746/http://blog.eogn.com/eastmans_online_genealogy/2006/10/who_was_colonel.html Eastman\u2019s Online Genealogy Newsletter]\n* {{Find a Grave|9251}}\n* [http://www.laokay.com/halac/RanchoLosFeliz.htm \"Rancho Los Feliz\"] \u2014 Kielbasa, John R., ''Historic Adobes of Los Angeles County''. Pittsburg: Dorrance Publishing Co., {{ISBN|0-8059-4172-X}}\n* [http://www.metnews.com/articles/2008/reminiscing071008.htm Reminiscing: Trial of Griffith J. Griffith Draws Wide Attention]; Grace, Roger M., ''Metropolitan News-Enterprise'' (Los Angeles), July 10, 2008\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Griffith, Griffith J.}}\n[[Category:Griffith Park| Griffith, Griffith J.]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:19th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from California]]\n[[Category:1850 births]]\n[[Category:1919 deaths]]\n[[Category:American prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Criminals of Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of California]]\n[[Category:American people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:Welsh emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Bridgend]]\n[[Category:History of Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Ashland, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Burials at Hollywood Forever Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman, philanthropist}}\n{{for|other people with the same name|Griffith Griffith (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Griffith J. Griffith\n| image       = Griffith Jenkins Griffith.jpg\n| image_size                =\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name                = Griffith Jenkins Griffith\n| birth_date                = {{birth date|1850|1|4}}\n| birth_place               = [[Bettws, Bridgend|Bettws]], [[Glamorgan]]shire, Wales\n| death_date                = {{death date and age|1919|7|6|1850|1|4}}\n| death_place               = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| body_discovered           =\n| resting_place             = [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery|Hollywood Memorial Cemetery]]<br>Los Angeles\n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| residence                 =\n| nationality               =\n| ethnicity                 =\n| citizenship               =\n| other_names               = Colonel Griffith J. Griffith\n| known_for                 = [[Philanthropy]]\n| education                 =\n| alma_mater                =\n| employer                  =\n| notable works             =\n| occupation                = [[Journalist]]<br>[[Mining]] and real estate magnate\n| years_active              =\n| home_town                 =\n| salary                    =\n| networth                  =\n| height                    =\n| weight                    =\n| title                     =\n| term                      =\n| predecessor               =\n| successor                 =\n| party                     =\n| opponents                 =\n| boards                    =\n| religion                  =\n| spouse                    = Mary Agnes Christina Mesmer (1887\u20131904; divorced)\n| partner                   =\n| children                  = Van M. Griffith (1888\u20131974)\n| parents                   =\n| relations                 =\n| callsign                  =\n| awards                    =\n| signature                 =\n| signature_alt             =\n| website                   =\n| footnotes                 =\n| box_width                 =\n| misc                      =\n}}\n\n'''Griffith Jenkins Griffith''' (January 4, 1850 \u2013 July 6, 1919) was a Welsh-born American [[industrialist]] and [[philanthropist]]. After amassing a significant fortune from a [[mining|mining syndicate]] in the 1880s, Griffith donated {{convert|3015|acre|km2}} to the [[Los Angeles|City of Los Angeles]] which became [[Griffith Park]], and he bequeathed the money to build the park's [[Greek Theatre (Los Angeles)|Greek Theatre]] and [[Griffith Observatory]]. Griffith's legacy was marred by his notorious shooting of his wife in 1903, a crime for which he served two years in prison.\n\n==Life==\n\n===Career and philanthropy===\n[[File:GriffithJGriffithStatue01.JPG|240px|thumb|Bronze statue of Griffith J. Griffith at [[Griffith Park]], Los Angeles (installed 1996)]]\nGriffith J. Griffith was born in [[Bettws, Bridgend|Bettws]], [[Glamorgan]]shire, [[Wales]], on January 4, 1850.<ref name=\"BBC historical\">{{cite web|title=BBC \u2013 south east Wales historical figures \u2013 Griffith J Griffith |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/southeast/halloffame/historical_figures/colonel_griffith.shtml|accessdate=May 14, 2010 |publisher=[[BBC]]|date=May 14, 2010|work=BBC website }}</ref> He immigrated to the United States in 1865, settling in [[Ashland, Pennsylvania]]. In 1873 he moved to San Francisco, California, and became manager of the Herald Publishing Company. In 1887 he married Mary Agnes Christina Mesmer (1864\u20131948).<ref>[http://www.ulwaf.com/LA-1900s/04.11.html#GriffithDivorce ''Los Angeles Daily Examiner''], November 5, 1904</ref>\n\nIn 1878 G. J. Griffith became mining correspondent for the ''Alta California'', a San Francisco newspaper. As a reporter he gained extensive knowledge of the mining industry on the Pacific Coast and in Nevada, which led to his employment by various mining syndicates. As a mining expert, Griffith acquired a fortune.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/expat/expatlife/8751943/The-Britons-who-made-their-mark-on-LA.html|title=The Britons who made their mark on LA|date=2011-09-11|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nIn 1882 Griffith moved to Los Angeles and purchased approximately {{convert|4000|acre|km2}} of the [[Rancho Los Feliz]] Mexican land grant. On December 16, 1896, Griffith and his wife Christina presented {{convert|3015|acre|km2}} of the Rancho Los Feliz to the city of Los Angeles for use as a public park. Griffith called it \"a Christmas present.\" After accepting the donation, the city passed an ordinance to name the property Griffith Park, in honor of the donor.<ref>\"Death Claims G. J. Griffith,\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', July 7, 1919</ref>\n\n\"It must be made a place of rest and relaxation for the masses, a resort for the rank and file, for the plain people,\" Griffith told the Los Angeles City Council when he donated the land. \"I consider it my obligation to make Los Angeles a happy, cleaner, and finer city. I wish to pay my debt of duty in this way to the community in which I have prospered.\" <ref>[http://www.ci.la.ca.us/RAP/dos/parks/griffithPK/gp_narrative.htm Griffith Park narrative] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115220537/http://www.ci.la.ca.us/rap/dos/parks/griffithpk/gp_narrative.htm |date=2010-01-15 }}, Department of Recreation and Parks, City of Los Angeles</ref>\n\nGriffith later donated another {{convert|1000|acre|km2}} along the [[Los Angeles River]].<ref>\"Griffith Park To Be Considered For Monument Status\"; Walton, Alice, City News Service, August 21, 2008</ref>\n\n===Crime===\nWhile vacationing in [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]] on September 3, 1903, Griffith shot his wife in the presidential suite of the [[:c:Category:Hotel Arcadia (Santa Monica, California)|Arcadia Hotel]], as she knelt on the floor before him. The shot did not kill her, but she was left disfigured and lost her right eye. Griffith was charged with assault with a deadly weapon with intent to commit murder. The prosecution was led by [[Henry Gage|Henry T. Gage]], former [[governor of California]]. Griffith was defended by attorney [[Earl Rogers]], whose cross-examination of the veiled Mrs. Griffith revealed that her husband\u2014generally thought to be a [[teetotaler]]\u2014was in fact a secret [[alcoholism|drunk]] who was subject to [[paranoia|paranoid]] delusions. Griffith was convicted of a lesser charge, assault with a deadly weapon. The judge sentenced him to two years in [[San Quentin State Prison]], instructing that he be given \"medical aid for his condition of alcoholic insanity\".<ref>[[Adela Rogers St. Johns|St. Johns, Adela Rogers]], ''Final Verdict''. Garden City, New York: Doubleday & Company, Inc., 1962, pp. 220\u2013239. \"That was where Earl Rogers began the first alcoholic [[insanity defense]],\" St. Johns wrote. \"Perhaps the first\u2014certainly one of the first\u2014times that alcohol was called to account in an American courtroom as a disease, a [[mental illness]], not just a sin or a crime or an indulgence\". (''Final Verdict'', p. 232.)</ref>\n\nOn November 4, 1904, while he was in prison, Mrs. Griffith was granted a divorce on the grounds of cruelty, and she was awarded custody of their 16-year-old son Vandell. The court also stated that G. J. Griffith would pay for his son's education at [[Stanford University]]. The decree was made in the record time of four and a half minutes.<ref>\"Mrs. Griffith Gets Divorce,\" ''Los Angeles Times'', November 5, 1904</ref>\n\n===Later life===\nG. J. Griffith was released from prison December 3, 1906, after serving nearly two years. His conduct at the penitentiary was called exemplary. Griffith returned to Los Angeles and began lecturing on prison reform.<ref>\"Griffith is Freed Today,\" ''Los Angeles Times'', December 3, 1906; \"Griffith to Lecture: Gone to San Francisco to Advocate Prison Reform Along Elmira Institution Lines,\" ''Los Angeles Times'', January 26, 1908</ref>\n\nIn December 1912 Griffith offered a second \"Christmas present\" to Los Angeles, in the form of a Greek Theater and a Hall of Science to be built at his expense in Griffith Park. The offer was accepted by the City Council, but members of the Park Commission objected and instituted a court action to block the donation. Griffith left the offer in his will. He died of liver disease on July 6, 1919. The bulk of his $1.5 million estate was bequeathed to the city for the building of the [[Greek Theater (Los Angeles)|Greek Theater]] (1929) and [[Griffith Observatory]] (1935).<ref>\"Death Claims G. J. Griffith,\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', July 7, 1919; \"City Gains by Griffith Will,\" ''Los Angeles Times'', July 12, 1919</ref> He is interred at the [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery]] in Los Angeles in the north end of Section 7, a.k.a. \"The Griffith Lawn\".<ref name=\"russell\">Russell, Ron (July 3, 1988). Splendor Fades at Final Resting Place of Famous, Almost Famous. ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''</ref>\n\nGriffith used the title of [[Colonel]], but official records of military service which support this rank have not been found. Evidence suggests the only military title he ever held was Major of rifle practice with the [[California National Guard]].<ref name=\"gurstelle2006\">Gurstelle, William (2006). ''Adventures from the Technology Underground.''  Clarkson Potter {{ISBN|978-1-4000-5082-6}}</ref><ref name=\"bell2011\">Bell, Alison (June 12, 2011). [http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-0612-then-20110612,0,5448370.story Colonel Griffith J. Griffith one of L.A.'s more colorful figures.] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Toomanylinks|date=January 2020}}\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/southeast/halloffame/historical_figures/colonel_griffith.shtml BBC biography]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100115220537/http://www.ci.la.ca.us/rap/dos/parks/griffithpk/gp_narrative.htm Griffith Park Narrative] (City of Los Angeles)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080513065309/http://www.griffithobservatory.org/obshist.html Griffith Observatory History]\n*[http://english.glendale.cc.ca.us/colonel.html Glendale College biography]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/1903/09/07/archives/millionaire-under-arrest-the-wife-of-col-griffith-of-los-angeles.html Millionaire Under Arrest; The Wife of Col. Griffith of Los Angeles Says He Shot Her]; ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 7, 1903\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061115071746/http://blog.eogn.com/eastmans_online_genealogy/2006/10/who_was_colonel.html Eastman\u2019s Online Genealogy Newsletter]\n* {{Find a Grave|9251}}\n* [http://www.laokay.com/halac/RanchoLosFeliz.htm \"Rancho Los Feliz\"] \u2014 Kielbasa, John R., ''Historic Adobes of Los Angeles County''. Pittsburg: Dorrance Publishing Co., {{ISBN|0-8059-4172-X}}\n* [http://www.metnews.com/articles/2008/reminiscing071008.htm Reminiscing: Trial of Griffith J. Griffith Draws Wide Attention]; Grace, Roger M., ''Metropolitan News-Enterprise'' (Los Angeles), July 10, 2008\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Griffith, Griffith J.}}\n[[Category:Griffith Park| Griffith, Griffith J.]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:19th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from California]]\n[[Category:1850 births]]\n[[Category:1919 deaths]]\n[[Category:American prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Criminals of Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of California]]\n[[Category:American people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:Welsh emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Bridgend]]\n[[Category:History of Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Ashland, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Burials at Hollywood Forever Cemetery]]\n", "nam