-prototype-manga-romance-dawn-gets-anime-adaptation-on-october-20|title=One Piece's Prototype Manga ROMANCE DAWN Gets Anime Adaptation on October 20|last=Komatsu|first=Mikikazu|website=Crunchyroll|language=en-us|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://one-piece.com/news/detail/20190330_8891.html|title=\u30a2\u30cb\u30e120\u5468\u5e74\u3092\u8a18\u5ff5\u3057\u3066\u300eONE PIECE\u300f\u306e\u539f\u70b9\u3092\u521d\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u5316\uff0110\u670820\u65e5(\u65e5)\u306b\u300eROMANCE DAWN\u300f\u306e\u653e\u9001\u6c7a\u5b9a!!! {{!}} \u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9|last=\u5c3e\u7530\u6804\u4e00\u90ce|website=ONE PIECE.com\uff08\u30ef\u30f3\u30d4\u30fc\u30b9 \u30c9\u30c3\u30c8\u30b3\u30e0\uff09|language=ja|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Shorts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 100%;\"\n!No.\n!'''Title'''\n!'''Release date'''\n!'''Length'''\n|-\n|1\n|''Jango's Dance Carnival''\n|March 3, 2001\n|5 minutes and 30 seconds\n|-\n|2\n|''Dream Soccer King''\n|March 2, 2002\n|5 minutes and 30 seconds\n|-\n|3\n|''Take Aim! The Pirate Baseball King''\n|March 6, 2004\n|5 minutes and 30 seconds\n|-\n|4\n|''ONE PIECE 3D! Trap Coaster''\n|December 1, 2011\n|12 minutes\n|}\n\n== Music ==\n{{Main|Music of One Piece}}\nMusic soundtracks have been released that are based on songs that premiered in the series. [[Kohei Tanaka (composer)|Kohei Tanaka]] and [[Shiro Hamaguchi]] composed the score for ''One Piece''.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://mediaarts-db.bunka.go.jp/an/anime_series/6951|title=One Piece|website=mediaarts-db.jp|publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]]|language=ja|accessdate=March 20, 2017}}</ref> Various [[Theme music|theme songs]] and [[character song]]s were released.\n\nThe anime television series consists of consists of 40 pieces of theme music; 22 opening themes and 18 ending themes. As of episode 279, ending themes were omitted and, starting from episode 326 onwards, opening themes were extended from 110 seconds long to 150 seconds long. In episodes 1-206 of [[Funimation]]'s English-language release of the series, the opening and ending themes were dubbed into English by various voice actors, before reverting to the Japanese versions from episodes 207 onwards and some openings were not licensed by Funimation's release.\n\nOn August 11, 2019, it was announced that Sakuramen, a musical group will be collaborating with [[Kohei Tanaka (composer)|Kohei Tanaka]] to compose music for anime's wano arc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://natalie.mu/comic/news/343304|title=\u300cONE PIECE\u300d\u30ef\u30ce\u56fd\u7de8\u306eBGM\u6f14\u594f\u306f\u548c\u697d\u5668\u6f14\u594f\u96c6\u56e3\u30fb\u685cmen\u304c\u62c5\u5f53\uff08\u30b3\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8\u3042\u308a\uff09|last=Inc|first=Natasha|website=\u30b3\u30df\u30c3\u30af\u30ca\u30bf\u30ea\u30fc|language=ja|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Other music ===\nOn December 23, 2019, a teaser video was uploaded in [[Arashi]]'s [[YouTube]] channel, in collaboration with the [[anime]]. The 39 second video for the song [[A-ra-shi: Reborn]], has the 5 animated members of the band mingling with the crew from the anime, up until the moment when Arashi is about to give a concert. The full version video was released on January 4, 2020. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://larepublica.pe/animes/2019/12/23/one-piece-y-arashi-realizan-colaboracion-para-videoclip-trailer-anime-manga-online-agrupacion-japonesa-luffy-satoshi-ono/|title=One Piece: Arashi realiza colaboraci\u00f3n con personajes del anime [VIDEO]|last=|first=|date=December 22, 2019|website=larepublica.pe|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223015401/https://larepublica.pe/animes/2019/12/23/one-piece-y-arashi-realizan-colaboracion-para-videoclip-trailer-anime-manga-online-agrupacion-japonesa-luffy-satoshi-ono/|archive-date=December 22, 2019|access-date=December 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== International broadcast and streaming ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Region / Continent\n!Region 