of 12.4%, behind ''[[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]]'' and ahead of ''[[Ojamajo Doremi]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050918133710/http://www.videor.co.jp/data/ratedata/backnum/1999/vol43.htm#comic|title=\u7a2e\u76ee\u5225\u9ad8\u4e16\u5e2f\u8996\u8074\u7387\u756a\u7d4410 Vol.43 '99 10/18(\u6708)~10/24(\u65e5)|language=Japanese|publisher=Video Research|url=http://www.videor.co.jp/data/ratedata/backnum/1999/vol43.htm#comic|archivedate=September 18, 2005|accessdate=March 3, 2009}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #149 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> In Japan, ''One Piece'' has consistently been among the top five animated shows in television viewer ratings, {{as of|2020|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-07-01/japan-animation-tv-ranking-june-18-24|title=Japan's Animation TV Ranking, June 18-24|work=Anime News Network|date=July 1, 2012|accessdate=August 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-08-24/japan-animation-tv-ranking-august-14-20/.120525|title=Japan's Animation TV Ranking, August 14-20|work=Anime News Network|date=August 20, 2017|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pineda |first1=Rafael Antonio |title=Japanese Animation TV Ranking, February 17-23 |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-02-28/japanese-animation-tv-ranking-february-17-23/.156943 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=[[Anime News Network]] |date=2020-02-28}}</ref> On international [[online video platform]]s, the ''One Piece'' anime got 1.9 million demand expressions per month in 2016, making it the year's most popular anime and fourteenth most popular TV show in the world, according to ''[[Business Insider]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/entertainment/data-reveals-the-20-most-popular-tv-shows-of-2016/14-Japans-One-Piece-with-1-9-million-demand-expressions-per-month-Now-in-its-18th-season-this-is-the-top-anime-series-in-the-world-/slideshow/56265071.cms|title=14) Japan\u2019s \"One Piece\" with 1.9 million demand expressions per month. Now in its 18th season, this is the top anime series in the world.|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/2017/01/01/one-piece-naruto-shippuden-nab-spots-as-two-of-2016-s-most-popul/|title=One Piece, Naruto: Shippuden Earn Spots As Two Of 2016\u2019s Most Popular Shows|website=Comicbook.com|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> On various occasions, the ''One Piece'' anime has topped Japan's DVD sales.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-07-27/japan-animation-dvd-ranking-july-12-18|title= Japan's Animation DVD Ranking, July 12\u201318 |work= [[Anime News Network]] |date= July 27, 2010 |accessdate= August 25, 2017}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #152 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-08-22/japan-animation-dvd-ranking-august-14-20 |title= Japanese Animation DVD Ranking, August 14\u201320 |work= [[Anime News Network]] |date= August 22, 2017 |accessdate= August 25, 2017 }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #153 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nIn a review of the second DVD release of 4Kids Entertainment's dub, Todd Douglass, Jr. of [[DVD Talk]] called its adaptation a \"shabby treatment\" resulting in an \"arguably less enjoyable rendition\". Douglass said that the 4Kids original opening was \"a crappy rap song\" and that the removal of whole scenes leaves a \"feeling that something is missing\". He later went on to say that \"Fans of the 'real' ''One Piece'' will want to skip picking [...] up [4Kids Entertainment's ''One Piece'' DVDs] until an uncut release is announced\", and also stated that \"kids may get into this version because it's what they have seen on TV\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/21195/one-piece-vol-2/|title=One Piece Vol 2|last=Douglass|first=Todd, Jr.|date=April 16, 2006|accessdate=April 26, 2009|publisher=[[DVD Talk]]}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #154 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> Margaret Veira of activeAnime praised the TV series' \"great\" animation, stating that \"It gives life and stays true to the style and characters of the manga.\" She notes the fight scenes in particular have \"a lot of energy to them\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://activeanime.com/html/2008/06/15/one-piece-season-one-first-voyage/ <!-- http://www.activeanime.com/html/content/view/3394/57/ --> |title=One Piece \u2013 Season One: First Voyage \u2013 Part One |first=Margaret |last=Veira |date=June 15, 2008 |accessdate=May 19, 2009 |publisher=Active Anime }} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #155 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> Patrick King of Animefringe comments that the art style of ''One Piece'' is \"very distinctive and fresh\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animefringe.com/magazine/2004/03/short/01.php|publisher=Animefringe|first=Patrick|last=King|author2=Kahn, Ridwan |author3=Font, Dillon |date=March 2004|accessdate=May 19, 2009|title=Manga Shorts}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #156 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref>\n\nIn a review of the first Funimation DVD release for Mania Entertainment, Bryce Coulter comments that ''One Piece'' is \"not your typical pirate adventure\" and that mixed with \"the right amount of random fun along with a shonen style storyline\" it becomes \"an appealing and fun romp\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mania.com/one-piece-season-1-part-1_article_80151.html |title=One Piece Season 1 Part 1 |first=Bryce |last=Coulter |date=June 5, 2008 |accessdate=July 6, 2009 |publisher=Mania Entertainment |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327131623/http://www.mania.com/one-piece-season-1-part-1_article_80151.html |archivedate=March 27, 2009 |df=mdy-all }} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #157 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> In a review of Funimation's second DVD release for Mania Entertainment, Bryce Coulter comments that \"You can tell that they are giving One Piece the attention that was neglected by 4Kids\" and that \"One Piece is a great tale of high-seas fun that will leave you wanting more!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mania.com/one-piece-season-1-part-2_article_80530.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501214011/http://www.mania.com/one-piece-season-1-part-2_article_80530.html|archivedate=May 1, 2011|title=One Piece Season 1 Part 2|first=Bryce|last=Coulter|publisher=Mania Entertainment|accessdate=July 6, 2009|date=October 1, 2008}} {{verify source |date=September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Indonesia, [[Global TV (Indonesia)|Global TV]] was reprimanded by the Indonesian Broadcasting Commission (KPI) for airing the anime television series. Nina Armando, member of the KPI and a lecturer at the University of Indonesia, said the show should not be aired at times when children are likely to watch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2008/07/08/comedy-hit-gets-warning-039vulgar039-content.html|title=Comedy hit gets warning for 'vulgar' content|last=Mauli|first=Erwida|work=The Jakarta Post |date=July 8, 2008|accessdate=March 11, 2009}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #159 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, where it is available on the [[Hulu]] streaming platform, ''One Piece'' was 2018's most [[binge-watch]]ed television show in the states of [[Illinois]] and [[Wisconsin]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Acuna |first1=Kirsten |title=The most-binged TV show in every state |url=https://www.thisisinsider.com/most-binged-tv-show-by-state-2018-8 |accessdate=March 1, 2019 |work=INSIDER |agency=[[Insider Inc.]] |date=August 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards and accolades ===\nThe first opening of the ''One Piece'' anime television series, \"We Are!\", won the [[Animation Kobe Theme Song Award]] of the year 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anime-kobe.jp/archive/2000/award/award_j2.html|title=ja:\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u795e\u6238\u8cde |publisher=[[Animation Kobe]] |accessdate=November 22, 2008 |language=Japanese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927175711/http://www.anime-kobe.jp/archive/2000/award/award_j2.html |archivedate=September 27, 2007 |df=mdy-all }} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #172 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> In February 2001, ''One Piece'' placed 9th among anime television series in Japan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2001-03-16/top-10-anime-in-japan|title=Top 10 Anime in Japan|accessdate=November 20, 2008|date=March 16, 2001|work=[[Anime News Network]]}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #173 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> In 2001, the readers of ''[[Animage]]'', a popular Japanese anime magazine, voted the anime television series in 5th place of The Readers' Picks for the Anime that should be remembered in the 21st Century.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2001-01-16/more-details-regarding-animage-top-100|accessdate=November 20, 2008|title=More details Regarding Animage Top 100|date=January 16, 2001|work=[[Anime News Network]]}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #174 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> In June 2002, ''Animage'' readers voted ''One Piece'' to be the 16th best new anime of the year 2001,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2002-05-10/june-animage-ranks-anime|accessdate=November 20, 2008|title=June Animage Ranks Anime|date=May 10, 2002|work=[[Anime News Network]]}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #175 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> and gave it another 16th place in 2004 in the category Favorite Anime Series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2004-05-12/animage-awards|title=Animage Awards|accessdate=November 20, 2008|date=May 12, 2004|work=[[Anime News Network]]}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #176 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> In a 2005 web poll by Japanese television network [[TV Asahi]] ''One Piece'' was voted 6th most popular animated TV series.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=November 20, 2008|date=September 23, 2005|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2005-09-23/tv-asahi-top-100-anime|title=TV Asahi Top 100 Anime|work=[[Anime News Network]]}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #177 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> Before the poll, Asahi TV broadcast another list based on a nationwide survey in which ''One Piece'' placed 4th among teenagers.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=November 20, 2008|date=September 23, 2005|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2005-09-23/tv-asahi-top-100-anime|title=TV Asahi Top 100 Anime \u2013 Part 2|work=[[Anime News Network]]}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #178 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> In 2006, it was elected 32nd of the Top 100 Japanese anime by TV Asahi and 21st by its viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv-asahi.co.jp/anime100/index_top.html|accessdate=November 18, 2008|title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u5168\u56fd\u5fb9\u5e95\u8abf\u67fb!\u597d\u304d\u306a\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0100|publisher=[[TV Asahi]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305070216/http://www.tv-asahi.co.jp/anime100/index_top.html|archivedate=March 5, 2009|url-status=dead|language=Japanese}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #179 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv-asahi.co.jp/anime100/contents/2006user/cur/|accessdate=November 18, 2008|title=ja:\u6708\u30d0\u30e92\u6642\u9593\u30b9\u30da\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u82b8\u80fd\u754c\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u901a\u304c\u96c6\u7d50!\u5fb9\u5e95\u8abf\u67fb\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0100|publisher=[[TV Asahi]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081225075715/http://www.tv-asahi.co.jp/anime100/contents/2006user/cur/|archivedate=December 25, 2008|language=Japanese}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #180 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> Funimation's first DVD release of the series \"One Piece: Season 1 First Voyage\" was nominated for the Fifth Annual TV DVD Awards.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2008-09-30/anime-nominated-for-tv-dvd-awards|work=[[Anime News Network]]|date=October 1, 2008|accessdate=January 29, 2009|title=Anime Nominated for TV DVD Awards}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447788 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #181 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of One Piece media|List of ''One Piece'' media]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n\n* [http://one-piece.com/comicsanime/anime.html ''One Piece'' official website] {{in lang|ja}}\n* [http://onepieceofficial.com/ Official anime website] of [[Funimation]]\n* {{ann|anime|836}}\n\n{{One Piece}}\n{{Toei Animation|state=collapsed}}\n{{Toonami-anime}}\n{{Gor\u014d Taniguchi}}\n{{Production I.G}}\n\n[[Category:One Piece media]]\n[[Category:1999 anime television series]]\n[[Category:1999 anime]]\n[[Category:Anime series based on manga]]\n[[Category:Adventure anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Asia Television Limited]]\n[[Category:Fantasy anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Fuji Television shows]]\n[[Category:Japanese action television series]]\n[[Category:Japanese fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Odex]]\n[[Category:Toei Animation]]\n[[Category:Toei Animation original video animation]]\n[[Category:Toei Animation television]]\n[[Category:Toonami]]\n[[Category:Funimation]]\n[[Category:Viz Media anime]]\n[[Category:Anime and manga featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese anime television series based on the One Piece manga series}}\n{{italic title|noerror|string=One Piece|all=yes}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Header\n| name            = One Piece\n| image           = One Piece Logo.svg\n| caption         = <!-- Per Infobox television, an image of the logo or title card does not need a caption -->\n| ja_kanji        = \u30ef\u30f3\u30d4\u30fc\u30b9\n| ja_romaji       = Wan P\u012bsu\n| genre                    = <!--Discuss in talk page before adding or removing genres, however, keep in mind [[WP:MOS-AM#Content]]. Thank you.-->[[Adventure fiction|Adventure]], [[fantasy]]<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.viz.com/one-piece|title=The Official Website for One Piece|author=|publisher=Viz Media|accessdate=October 27, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = tv series\n| director        = {{ubl|[[K\u014dnosuke Uda]]|{{Small|(#1\u2013278)}}|Junji Shimizu|{{Small|(#131\u2013159)}}|Munehisa Sakai|{{Small|(#244\u2013372)}}|Hiroaki Miyamoto|{{small|(#352\u2013679)}}|Toshinori Fukazawa| {{Small|(#663\u2013891)}}|Satoshi It\u014d|{{Small|(#780\u2013782)}}|[[Tatsuya Nagamine]]|{{Small|(#780\u2013782; #892-)}}|[[Aya Komaki]]|{{Small|(#892-)|}}}}<!-- Just series directors, not episode directors -->\n| producer        = \n| writer          = {{ubl|Junki Takegami {{Small|(#1\u2013195)}}|Hirohiko Uesaka {{Small|(#196\u2013798)}}|[[Sh\u014dji Yonemura]] {{Small|(#799\u2013)}}}}\n| music           = {{ubl|[[Kohei Tanaka (composer)|Kohei Tanaka]]|[[Shir\u014d Hamaguchi]]|Sakuramen}}\n| studio          = [[Toei Animation]]\n| licensee        = {{English anime licensee\n  | AUS = [[Madman Entertainment]]\n  | NA  = [[Funimation]]\n  | UK  = [[Manga Entertainment]]\n}}\n| network         = [[Fuji Network System|FNS]] ([[Fuji TV]])\n| network_en      = {{English anime network\n | SEA = [[Animax Asia]]\n | AU = [[Network Ten]], [[Cartoon Network (Australia)|Cartoon Network]] ([[Toonami (Australia)|Toonami]])\n | CA = [[YTV (TV channel)|YTV]]\n | NZ = [[Cartoon Network (Australia)|Cartoon Network]], [[TV2 (New Zealand)|TV2]]\n | UK = [[Toonami (UK & Ireland)|Toonami]], [[CN Too]]\n | US = {{ubl|[[Cartoon Network]]/[[Adult Swim]] ([[Toonami]])|[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] ([[4Kids TV]])|[[TV Japan]] {{small|(subtitled)}}}}\n | ZA = [[SABC 2]]\n}}\n| first           = October 20, 1999\n| episodes        = 927\n| episode_list    = Lists of One Piece episodes\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Footer}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''One Piece'''''|\u30ef\u30f3\u30d4\u30fc\u30b9|Wan P\u012bsu|lead=yes}} is a Japanese [[anime]] [[television series]] adapted from the [[One Piece|manga of the same name]] by [[Eiichiro Oda]]. The story follows the adventures of [[Monkey D. Luffy]], a boy whose body gained the properties of rubber after unintentionally eating a Devil Fruit. With his crew of pirates, named the [[Straw Hat Pirates]], Luffy explores the Grand Line in search of the world's ultimate treasure known as \"One Piece\" in order to become the next Pirate King.\n\nProduced by [[Toei Animation]], ''One Piece'' premiered in Japan on [[Fuji TV]] on October 20, 1999, has aired more than 900 episodes, and has been exported to various countries around the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=One Piece|url=http://mediaarts-db.bunka.go.jp/an/anime_series/6951|website=mediaarts-db.jp|publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]]|accessdate=March 20, 2017|language=ja}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908442942 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #62 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref>\n\nIn Japan, ''One Piece'' has consistently been among the top five animated shows in television viewer ratings, {{as of|2020|lc=y}}. On international [[online video platform]]s, the ''One Piece'' anime got 1.9 million demand expressions per month in 2016, making it the year's most popular anime and fourteenth most popular TV show in the world, according to ''[[Business Insider]]''.\n\n== Series overview ==\n{{Further|Lists of One Piece episodes}}{{See also|List of One Piece episodes (seasons 1\u20138)|List of One Piece episodes (seasons 9\u201314)|List of One Piece episodes (seasons 15\u2013current)}}\n{{One Piece series overview}}\n\n== Main voice cast ==\n{{Further|List of One Piece characters}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse;\"\n!Character\n!Japanese\n!English\n([[Funimation]])\n|-\n|'''[[Monkey D. Luffy]]'''\n|[[Mayumi Tanaka]]\n|[[Colleen Clinkenbeard]]\n|-\n|'''[[Roronoa Zoro]]'''\n|[[Kazuya Nakai]]\n|[[Christopher R. Sabat]]\n|-\n|[[Nami (One Piece)|'''Nami''']]\n|[[Akemi Okamura]]\n|[[Luci Christian]]\n|-\n|'''[[Usopp]]'''\n|[[Kappei Yamaguchi]]\n|[[Sonny Strait]]\n|-\n|'''[[Vinsmoke Sanji]]'''\n|[[Hiroaki Hirata]]\n|[[Eric Vale]]\n|-\n|[[Tony-Tony Chopper|'''Tony Tony Chopper''']]\n|[[Ikue \u014ctani]]\n|[[Brina Palencia]]\n|-\n|'''[[Nico Robin]]'''\n|[[Yuriko Yamaguchi (voice actor)|Yuriko Yamaguchi]]\n|[[Stephanie Young]]\n|-\n|[[Franky (One Piece)|'''Franky''']]\n|[[Kazuki Yao]]\n|[[Patrick Seitz]]\n|-\n|[[Brook (One Piece)|'''Brook''']]\n|[[Ch\u014d]]\n|[[Ian Sinclair (voice actor)|Ian Sinclair]]\n|}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== English localization and Broadcasting ===\nOn June 8, 2004, [[4Licensing Corporation|4Kids Entertainment]] acquired the license for distribution of ''One Piece'' in North America.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2004-06-08/4kids-announces-one-piece|title=4Kids Announces One Piece|work=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 8, 2004|accessdate=June 8, 2004}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #65 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> 4Kids contracted Viz Media to handle home video distribution. 4Kids' in-house musicians wrote a new background score and theme song nicknamed \"Pirate Rap\". 4Kids' dub mandated edits for [[Editing of anime in American distribution|content and length]], which reduced the first 143 episodes into 104.<ref>''One Piece'' [[4Kids Entertainment|4Kids]] dub, episodes 1-104 (1-143 uncut) {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #66 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> Initially, 4Kids originally created an English version of the first opening theme, \"We Are!\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interview/2005-04-24/alfred-r-kahn|title=Alfred R. Kahn Interview|accessdate=April 24, 2005|date=April 24, 2005|work=[[Anime News Network]]}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #67 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> It premiered in the United States on September 18, 2004 on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] network as part of the weekend programming block FoxBox TV, and later aired on [[Cartoon Network]] on their Saturday night action programming block, [[Toonami]] in April 2005. It also aired in other blocks and line-ups, such as its Monday-Thursday night prime-time line-up and its ''Miguzi'' weekday after-school action block in 2006. Production was halted in 2006 after episode 143/104.<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=Pirate King's last stand |magazine=[[Newtype USA]] |publisher=A.D. Vision |volume=6 |issue=2 |page=118 |date=February 2007 |issn=1541-4817 }} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #68 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2006-12-06/4kids-cancels-one-piece-production|title=4Kids Cancels One Piece Production|work=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 6, 2006|accessdate=December 6, 2006}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #69 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> Viz also ceased its home video release of the series after volume 11. On July 22, 2010, an interview with [[Anime News Network]] and Mark Kirk, senior vice-president of digital media for 4Kids Entertainment, revealed that 4Kids acquired ''One Piece'' as part of a package deal with other anime, and that the company did not screen the series before licensing it. However, once 4Kids realized ''One Piece'' was not appropriate for their intended demographic, the company decided to edit it into a more child-oriented series until they had an opportunity to legally drop the license. Kirk said the experience of producing ''One Piece'' \"ruined the company's reputation\". Since then, 4Kids established a stricter set of guidelines, checks, and balances to determine which anime the company acquires.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/anncast/2010-07-22|title=Kirk Up Your Ears|work=Anime News Network|date=July 22, 2010|accessdate=July 22, 2010}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #70 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2007, [[Funimation]] licensed the series and started production on an English-language release of ''One Piece''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2007-04-13/funimation-acquires-one-piece|title=Funimation Acquires One Piece|work=[[Anime News Network]]|date=April 13, 2007|accessdate=April 13, 2007}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #71 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> In an interview with voice actor [[Christopher Sabat]], he stated that Funimation had been interested in acquiring ''One Piece'' from the very beginning, and produced a \"test episode,\" in which Sabat portrayed the character of [[Helmeppo]] and [[Eric Vale]] played the part of the main character, Monkey D. Luffy. (They would later go on to provide the English voices for Roronoa Zoro and [[Sanji (One Piece)|Sanji]], respectively.)<ref>{{cite web|first=Zach|last=Logan|date=December 18, 2010|url=http://onepiecepodcast.com/2010/12/18/episode-148-the-mute-button-chris-sabat/|title=The Unofficial One Piece Podcast, Episode 148|accessdate=January 4, 2011|publisher=The Unofficial One Piece Podcast}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #72 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> After resuming production of the renewed English dub, which featured less censorship because of fewer restrictions on cable programming, Funimation released its first uncut, bilingual DVD box set containing 13 episodes on May 27, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|first=Bryce |last=Coulter |date=June 5, 2008 |url=http://www.mania.com/one-piece-season-1-part-1_article_80151.html |title=One Piece Season 1 Part 1 |accessdate=March 30, 2010 |publisher=Mania Entertainment |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327131623/http://www.mania.com/one-piece-season-1-part-1_article_80151.html |archivedate=March 27, 2009 |df=mdy-all }} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #73 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> Similarly sized sets followed with fourteen sets released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rightstuf.com/cgi-bin/catalogmgr/NJfZumwqXV6TkVQgUJ/browse/item/88880/4/0/0|title=Right Stuf's listing for One Piece: Season Three, Third Voyage|website=RightStuf|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130615053859/http://www.rightstuf.com/cgi-bin/catalogmgr/NJfZumwqXV6TkVQgUJ/browse/item/88880/4/0/0|archive-date=June 15, 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=October 20, 2014}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #74 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> The Funimation-dubbed episodes premiered on Cartoon Network on September 29, 2007 and aired until its removal on March 22, 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2008-03-29/cartoon-network-has-no-plans-for-one-piece-return|title=Cartoon Network Has No Plans for One Piece's Return (Updated)|date=March 29, 2008|accessdate=March 29, 2008|work=[[Anime News Network]]}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #75 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> On October 28, 2011, Funimation posted a press release on their official website confirming the acquisition of episodes 206\u2013263, and the aspect ratio, beginning with episode 207, would be changed to the 16:9 widescreen format.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rojas|first=Justin|publisher=Funimation Entertainment|title=Funimation Entertainment Acquires One Piece \u2013 Season Four|url=https://www.funimation.com/blog/2011/10/28/funimation-entertainment-acquires-one-piece-season-four/|date=October 28, 2011|accessdate=October 28, 2011}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #76 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> On May 18, 2013, the uncut series began airing on [[Adult Swim]]'s revived Toonami late-night programming block from episode 207 onward.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-03-10/one-piece-to-air-on-adult-swim-toonami-block |title=One Piece to Air on Adult Swim's Toonami Block \u2013 News |work=Anime News Network |date=March 13, 2013 |accessdate=March 17, 2013}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #77 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> ''One Piece'' was removed from the Toonami block after March 18, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2017/03/10-1/toonami-says-goodbye-to-one-piece-and-hello-tokyo-ghoul|title=Toonami Says Goodbye to \"One Piece\" (And Hello to \"Tokyo Ghoul\")|last=Green|first=Scott|date=March 11, 2017|work=Crunchyroll|access-date=April 2, 2017|language=en}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #78 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Funimation, Toei Animation, Shueisha, and Fuji TV announced they would [[simulcast]] stream the series within an hour of the weekly Japanese broadcast at no charge.<ref>{{cite press release|publisher=Funimation Entertainment|title=FUNimation Entertainment, Toei Animation, Shueisha and Fuji TV Announce Online Simulcast of One Piece|url=http://www.toei-anim.com/news/onepiece.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209122853/http://www.toei-anim.com/news/onepiece.pdf|archivedate=February 9, 2014|date=May 14, 2009|accessdate=October 10, 2010}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #79 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> Originally scheduled to begin on May 30, 2009, with episode 403, a lack of security resulted in a leak of the episode, and Funimation delayed the offer until episode 415 on August 29, 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-05-30/funimation-cancels-one-piece-simulcast|title=Funimation Cancels One Piece Simulcast (Update 2)|work=[[Anime News Network]]|date=May 30, 2009|accessdate=May 30, 2009}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #80 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.funimation.com/f_index.cfm?page=news&id=590 |title=Funimation Entertainment Announces Online Return of One Piece |accessdate=August 18, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100205201712/http://funimation.com/f_index.cfm?page=news&id=590 |archivedate=February 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #81 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-08-18/funimation-to-relaunch-one-piece-streams-on-saturday|title=Funimation to Relaunch One Piece Simulcast on August 29|work=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 18, 2009|accessdate=August 18, 2009}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #82 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref>\n\nOn February 12, 2013, it was announced that [[Manga Entertainment]] would start releasing the Funimation dub of ''One Piece'' in the United Kingdom in a DVD box set format.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/home-entertainment/toei-and-manga-ent-take-one-piece-to-u-k/|title=Toei and Manga Ent. Take 'One Piece' to U.K.|last=Zahed|first=Ramin|date=February 12, 2013|work=Animation Magazine|access-date=April 2, 2017|language=en-US}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #83 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> [[Crunchyroll]] began simulcasting the series on November 2, 2013, for the United States, Canada, South Africa, Australia, New Zealand, and Latin America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://operationrainfall.com/2013/10/31/one-piece-simulcast-crunchyroll/|title=One Piece Anime to Be Simulcast on Crunchyroll|last=Chetkauskas|first=Eric|date=October 31, 2013|website=oprainfall|access-date=April 2, 2017}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908447368 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/908440702 cite #84 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> Crunchyroll later expanded access to the United Kingdom and Ireland, as well as a majority of European territories, on February 22, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://animeuknews.net/2020/02/crunchyroll-expands-one-piece-legal-streaming-to-uk-ireland-and-many-more-eu-mena-territories/|title=Crunchyroll Expands One Piece Legal Streaming to UK & Ireland and many more EU/MENA territories|date=January 22, 2020|publisher=Anime UK News|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Films ==\n{{main|List of One Piece films}}Fourteen animated theatrical films based on the ''One Piece'' series have been released in Japan. The films are typically released in March in accordance with the spring vacation of Japanese schools.<ref name=\"10th Movie\">{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2008-12-31/2009-one-piece-movie-to-mark-anime-10th-anniversary|title=One Piece Movie 10 tentative information|work=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=January 7, 2009}}</ref> The films feature self-contained, completely original plots, or alternate retellings of story arcs with animation of a higher quality than what the weekly anime allows. The first three films were typically double features paired up with other anime films, and were thus, usually an hour or less in length. The films themselves offer contradictions in both chronology and design that make them incompatible with a single continuity. Funimation has licensed the eighth, tenth, twelfth and thirteenth films for release in North America, and these films have received in-house dubs by the company.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-04-07/funimation-to-release-one-piece-film/z-on-home-video|title=Funimation to Release One Piece Film: Z on Home Video|date=April 7, 2014|work=Anime News Network|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 100%;\"\n!No.\n!'''Title'''\n!'''Director'''\n!'''Writer'''\n!'''Release date'''\n!'''Runtime'''\n|-\n|1\n|''[[One Piece: The Movie]]''\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Junji Shimizu\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Michiru Shimada]]\n|March 4, 2000\n|51 minutes\n|-\n|2\n|''Clockwork Island Adventure''\n|March 3, 2001\n|55 minutes\n|-\n|3\n|''Chopper's Kingdom on the Island of Strange Animals''\n|March 2, 2002\n|56 minutes\n|-\n|4\n|''[[One Piece The Movie: Dead End no B\u014dken|Dead End Adventure]]''\n|[[Konosuke Uda]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Yoshiyuki Suga\n|March 1, 2003\n|1 hr 35 min\n|-\n|5\n|''[[One Piece: The Cursed Holy Sword|The Cursed Holy Sword]]''\n|Kazuhisa Takenouchi\n|March 6, 2004\n|1 hr 35 min\n|-\n|6\n|''[[One Piece: Baron Omatsuri and the Secret Island|Baron Omatsuri and the Secret Island]]''\n|[[Mamoru Hosoda]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Masahiro It\u014d\n|March 5, 2005\n|1 hr 32 min\n|-\n|7\n|''Giant Mecha Soldier of Karakuri Castle''\n|K\u014dnosuke Uda\n|March 4, 2006\n|1 hr 35 min\n|-\n|8\n|''[[One Piece Movie: The Desert Princess and the Pirates: Adventures in Alabasta|The Desert Princess and the Pirates: Adventures in Alabasta]]''\n|Takahiro Imamura\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Hirohiko Kamisaka\n|March 3, 2007\n|1 hr 30 min\n|-\n|9\n|''Episode of Chopper Plus: Bloom in the Winter, Miracle Cherry Blossom''\n|Junji Shimizu\n|March 1, 2008\n|1 hr 53 min\n|-\n|10\n|''[[One Piece Film: Strong World]]''\n|Munehisa Sakai\n|December 12, 2009\n|1 hr 53 min\n|-\n|11\n|''Straw Hat Chase''\n|Hiroyuki Sat\u014d\n|Yasuyuki Tsutsumi\n|March 19, 2011\n|30 minutes\n|-\n|12\n|''[[One Piece Film: Z]]''\n|[[Tatsuya Nagamine]]\n|Osamu Suzuki\n|December 15, 2012\n|1 hr 47 min\n|-\n|13\n|''[[One Piece Film: Gold]]''\n|Hiroaki Miyamoto\n|Tsutomu Kuroiwa\n|July 23, 2016\n|2 hours\n|- style=\"background:#b6fcb6;\